## Alternative Approaches and Considerations

### Revenue from Name, Image, and Likeness (NIL) Rights

Recent changes have allowed college athletes to profit from their name, image, and likeness independently of their schools. This approach lets athletes earn money through endorsements, autograph sessions, and merchandise sales without schools directly paying salaries. It also avoids many complications related to institutional budgets and amateurism ([Future of Working, n.d.](https://futureofworking.com/6-advantages-and-disadvantages-of-paying-college-athletes/)).

### Scholarships as a Form of Payment

Scholarships remain the primary form of compensation for college athletes, covering tuition, room, board, and other expenses. Some argue this is sufficient payment, especially given the educational opportunities provided ([Vittana, 2018](https://vittana.org/14-should-college-athletes-be-paid-pros-and-cons)).

### Revenue Sharing and Stipends

Some proposals suggest providing athletes with stipends or revenue-sharing arrangements based on the income generated by their sports programs. This could balance financial support with institutional sustainability ([Gillespie, 2017](https://repository.tcu.edu/handle/116099117/19868)).

